{{infobox religious building |name=Ārīugan }} '''Higashi Utaki''' (東御嶽, Āruugan, Ārīugan<ref name="okinawastory">{{Cite web|ja | title = Aragusuku Island | url = https://www.okinawastory.jp/spot/1304 | work = Okinawa Story | publisher = Okinawa Convention & Visitors Bureau | accessdate = 2023-05-14 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20221128013234/https://www.okinawastory.jp/spot/1304 | archivedate = 2022-11-28}}</ref>) is an {{ill|Utaki (Okinawa)|ja|御嶽}} located on {{ill|Aragusuku Island|ja|新城島}} (Kamiji Island), in {{ill|Taketomi, Okinawa|ja|竹富町}}, {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県}}. It is also known as '''Iso Utaki''' (磯御嶽, Ishāugan, Ishōugan), '''Gusuku Utaki''' (グスクウガン, Kūsukuugan<ref name="hesiki_1975">{{cite journal|ja | title = Akamuta and Kuromuta Rituals on Aragusuku Island: Notes on the Ufupuru of Kamiji | author = Reiji Heshiki | url = https://hdl.handle.net/2308/1372 | journal = Okinawa International University Bulletin of Sociology | issn = 02870681 | publisher = Okinawa International University | year = 1975 | month = 03 | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages = 55-69}}</ref>), and '''Zannuon'''<ref name="shojiten">{{cite book|ja | title = Yaeyama Small Encyclopedia | page = 91 | author = Tsuneshin Sakihara | publisher = Border Ink | date = 1999-08-01}}</ref>. It is sometimes colloquially referred to as the "Mermaid Shrine" (人魚神社, Ningyo Jinja), though it is not a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|ja | title = Aragusuku Island | encyclopedia= Kadokawa Japan Place Name Encyclopedia 47 Okinawa Prefecture | author = Kadokawa Japan Place Name Compilation Committee | date= 1986-07-08 | publisher= Kadokawa Shoten | page = 130}}</ref>.
== Overview == Of the four Utaki on Kamiji Island, Higashi Utaki is the oldest and is regarded as the second holiest site after {{ill|Bi Utaki|ja|美御嶽}} (Naha-ugan). It is located east (Āru) of the only settlement on Kamiji Island and enshrines the deity of {{ill|Ryūgū|ja|龍宮}}<ref name="hesiki_1975" /><ref name="okinawastory" />. The site is situated on a rocky plateau, and behind the worship area is the remains of an enclosure surrounded by stone walls<ref name="shojiten" />. Fragments of {{ill|Panari pottery|ja|パナリ焼き}} have been found around the site<ref name="shojiten" />.
Access to the Utaki is restricted, with a "No Entry" sign posted on the path leading to it. Only designated shrine caretakers are permitted to enter beyond the torii gate<ref name="okinawatimes_1999-12-18">{{cite news|ja | title = Island Life: Seafarers' Living (8) Aragusuku Island (Taketomi Town) | url = http://www.okinawatimes.co.jp/spe/yuku991218.html | newspaper = Okinawa Times | date = 1999-12-18 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20000901000807/http://www.okinawatimes.co.jp/spe/yuku991218.html | archivedate = 2000-09-01}}</ref>.
== History == Higashi Utaki is also referred to as the "Original Utaki" (Mutuuugan), as it is believed to have been established when people first settled on Kamiji Island<ref name="hesiki_1975" />. Though the history of the island remains unclear, records from [[1477]] indicate that three shipwrecked Koreans from [[Jeju Island]] were rescued and repatriated through Aragusuku, confirming that the island had a settled population at that time<ref name="shojiten" />.
During the era when the {{ill|Ryukyu Kingdom|ja|琉球王国}} imposed the {{ill|Head Tax|ja|人頭税}}, Aragusuku Island, which had limited fresh water and farmland, was required to provide dried {{ill|Dugong|ja|ジュゴン}} meat as tribute. The skulls of captured dugongs were offered at Higashi Utaki as part of prayers for abundant marine harvests<ref name="hesiki_1975" /><ref name="okinawastory" /><ref name="shojiten" />. At one time, a large number of dugong skulls were piled at the site<ref name="shojiten" />, but theft and other factors have significantly reduced their number<ref name="okinawatimes_1999-12-18" />. The name "Zannuon" means "Dugong Utaki," and "Iso" in "Iso Utaki" can also mean "sea"<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
== Rituals == Higashi Utaki is a focal point for prayers during the three major festivals of the island: the Harvest Festival (Buru), the Seasonal Festival (Siichi), and the Kichugan Festival (Kichugan)<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
The {{ill|Kaminchu|ja|神司}} (priestess) responsible for the shrine traditionally comes from the Asato family (Āru Asadei), while the {{ill|Kamanga|ja|カマンガー}} (assistant male priest) comes from the Shin family (Āraei)<ref name="hesiki_1975" />. As of 2013, the shrine has no serving priestess<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
