{{infobox religious building |name=Ārīugan }} '''Higashi Utaki''' (東御嶽, Āruugan, Ārīugan<ref name="okinawastory">{{Cite web|ja | title = Aragusuku Island | url = https://www.okinawastory.jp/spot/1304 | work = Okinawa Story | publisher = Okinawa Convention & Visitors Bureau | accessdate = 2023-05-14 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20221128013234/https://www.okinawastory.jp/spot/1304 | archivedate = 2022-11-28}}</ref>) is an {{ill|Utaki (Okinawa)|ja|御嶽}} located on {{ill|Aragusuku Island|ja|新城島}} (Kamiji Island), in {{ill|Taketomi, Okinawa|ja|竹富町}}, {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県}}. It is also known as '''Iso Utaki''' (磯御嶽, Ishāugan, Ishōugan), '''Gusuku Utaki''' (グスクウガン, Kūsukuugan<ref name="hesiki_1975">{{cite journal|ja | title = Akamuta and Kuromuta Rituals on Aragusuku Island: Notes on the Ufupuru of Kamiji | author = Reiji Heshiki | url = https://hdl.handle.net/2308/1372 | journal = Okinawa International University Bulletin of Sociology | issn = 02870681 | publisher = Okinawa International University | year = 1975 | month = 03 | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages]][[Category:= 55-69}}</ref>), and '''Zannuon'''<ref name="shojiten">{{cite book|ja | title = Yaeyama Small Encyclopedia | page = 91 | author = Tsuneshin Sakihara | publisher = Border Ink | date = 1999-08-01}}</ref>. It is sometimes colloquially referred to as the "Mermaid Shrine" (人魚神社, Ningyo Jinja), though it is not a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|ja | title = Aragusuku Island | encyclopedia= Kadokawa Japan Place Name Encyclopedia 47 Okinawa Prefecture | author = Kadokawa Japan Place Name Compilation Committee | date= 1986-07-08 | publisher= Kadokawa Shoten | page = 130}}</ref>.
