During the era when the {{ill|Ryukyu Kingdom|ja|琉球王国}} imposed the {{ill|Head Tax|ja|人頭税}}, Aragusuku Island, which had limited fresh water and farmland, was required to provide dried {{ill|Dugong|ja|ジュゴン}} meat as tribute. The skulls of captured dugongs were offered at Higashi Utaki as part of prayers for abundant marine harvests<ref name="hesiki_1975" /><ref name="okinawastory" /><ref name="shojiten" />. At one time, a large number of dugong skulls were piled at the site<ref name="shojiten" />, but theft and other factors have significantly reduced their number<ref name="okinawatimes_1999-12-18" />. The name "Zannuon" means "Dugong Utaki," and "Iso" in "Iso Utaki" can also mean "sea"<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
== Rituals == Higashi Utaki is a focal point for prayers during the three major festivals of the island: the Harvest Festival (Buru), the Seasonal Festival (Siichi), and the Kichugan Festival (Kichugan)<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
The {{ill|Kaminchu|ja|神司}} (priestess) responsible for the shrine traditionally comes from the Asato family (Āru Asadei), while the {{ill|Kamanga|ja|カマンガー}} (assistant male priest) comes from the Shin family (Āraei)<ref name="hesiki_1975" />. As of 2013, the shrine has no serving priestess<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
