{{draft categories| [[Category:= 55-69}}</ref>), and '''Zannuon'''<ref name="shojiten">{{cite book|ja | title = Yaeyama Small Encyclopedia | page = 91 | author = Tsuneshin Sakihara | publisher = Border Ink | date = 1999-08-01}}</ref>. It is sometimes colloquially referred to as the "Mermaid Shrine" (人魚神社, Ningyo Jinja), though it is not a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|ja | title = Aragusuku Island | encyclopedia= Kadokawa Japan Place Name Encyclopedia 47 Okinawa Prefecture | author = Kadokawa Japan Place Name Compilation Committee | date= 1986-07-08 | publisher= Kadokawa Shoten | page = 130}}</ref>.
== Overview == Of the four Utaki on Kamiji Island, Higashi Utaki is the oldest and is regarded as the second holiest site after {{ill|Bi Utaki|ja|美御嶽}} (Naha-ugan). It is located east (Āru) of the only settlement on Kamiji Island and enshrines the deity of {{ill|Ryūgū|ja|龍宮}}<ref name="hesiki_1975" /><ref name="okinawastory" />. The site is situated on a rocky plateau, and behind the worship area is the remains of an enclosure surrounded by stone walls<ref name="shojiten" />. Fragments of {{ill|Panari pottery|ja|パナリ焼き}} have been found around the site<ref name="shojiten" />.
Access to the Utaki is restricted, with a "No Entry" sign posted on the path leading to it. Only designated shrine caretakers are permitted to enter beyond the torii gate<ref name="okinawatimes_1999-12-18">{{cite news|ja | title = Island Life: Seafarers' Living (8) Aragusuku Island (Taketomi Town) | url = http://www.okinawatimes.co.jp/spe/yuku991218.html | newspaper = Okinawa Times | date = 1999-12-18 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20000901000807/http://www.okinawatimes.co.jp/spe/yuku991218.html | archivedate = 2000-09-01}}</ref>.
