{{DEFAULTSORT:A}} {{DEFAULTSORT:Ārīugan}}

{{infobox religious building |name=Ārīugan }} '''Higashi Utaki''' (東御嶽, Āruugan, Ārīugan<ref name="okinawastory">{{Cite web|ja | title = Aragusuku Island | url = https://www.okinawastory.jp/spot/1304 | work = Okinawa Story | publisher = Okinawa Convention & Visitors Bureau | accessdate = 2023-05-14 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20221128013234/https://www.okinawastory.jp/spot/1304 | archivedate = 2022-11-28}}</ref>) is an {{ill|Utaki (Okinawa)|ja|御嶽|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located on {{ill|Aragusuku Island|ja|新城島|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Kamiji Island), in {{ill|Taketomi, Okinawa|ja|竹富町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is also known as '''Iso Utaki''' (磯御嶽, Ishāugan, Ishōugan), '''Gusuku Utaki''' (グスクウガン, Kūsukuugan<ref name="hesiki_1975">{{cite journal|ja | title = Akamuta and Kuromuta Rituals on Aragusuku Island: Notes on the Ufupuru of Kamiji | author = Reiji Heshiki | url = https://hdl.handle.net/2308/1372 | journal = Okinawa International University Bulletin of Sociology | issn = 02870681 | publisher = Okinawa International University | year = 1975 | month = 03 | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages]] indicate that three shipwrecked Koreans from [[Jeju Island]] were rescued and repatriated through Aragusuku, confirming that the island had a settled population at that time<ref name="shojiten" />.
During the era when the {{ill|Ryukyu Kingdom|ja|琉球王国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} imposed the {{ill|Head Tax|ja|人頭税|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Aragusuku Island, which had limited fresh water and farmland, was required to provide dried {{ill|Dugong|ja|ジュゴン|qq=draft|qq=draft}} meat as tribute. The skulls of captured dugongs were offered at Higashi Utaki as part of prayers for abundant marine harvests<ref name="hesiki_1975" /><ref name="okinawastory" /><ref name="shojiten" />. At one time, a large number of dugong skulls were piled at the site<ref name="shojiten" />, but theft and other factors have significantly reduced their number<ref name="okinawatimes_1999-12-18" />. The name "Zannuon" means "Dugong Utaki," and "Iso" in "Iso Utaki" can also mean "sea"<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
== Rituals == Higashi Utaki is a focal point for prayers during the three major festivals of the island: the Harvest Festival (Buru), the Seasonal Festival (Siichi), and the Kichugan Festival (Kichugan)<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
The {{ill|Kaminchu|ja|神司|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (priestess) responsible for the shrine traditionally comes from the Asato family (Āru Asadei), while the {{ill|Kamanga|ja|カマンガー|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (assistant male priest) comes from the Shin family (Āraei)<ref name="hesiki_1975" />. As of 2013, the shrine has no serving priestess<ref name="hesiki_1975" />.
